We can see that 52 attributes do not have any missing data. The only column with the missing data is Order Zipcode.¶

This is an important feature for analysis to find out which zipcode sees the most fraud in the supply chain cycle and which doesnt.¶

A company cna then use the inference and define strategies to that will mittigate the fraud happening in those areas.¶

From this we can interpret that null values are present in the columns 'Order Zipcode','Customer zipcode', 'Customer Lname'

Days for shipping (real) vs. days for shipment (scheduled)¶

Correlation coefficient: 0.515880 Strength: Moderate Direction: Positive Interpretation: Orders that take longer to ship are more likely to be shipped late. Possible explanations:

Orders that are more complex or require more processing time may take longer to ship. Orders may be delayed due to unforeseen circumstances, such as bad weather or transportation problems. Retailers may underestimate the time it takes to ship orders, especially during peak periods. Recommendations:

Retailers should strive to accurately estimate shipping times and communicate these estimates to customers upfront. Retailers should have a plan in place to deal with unexpected delays. Retailers should consider offering expedited shipping options to customers who need their orders quickly.

Days for shipping (real) vs. late_delivery_risk¶

Correlation coefficient: 0.401415 Strength: Moderate Direction: Positive Interpretation: Orders that take longer to ship are more likely to be shipped late. Possible explanations:

Orders that are shipped late are more likely to be delayed in transit. Orders that are shipped to remote locations are more likely to be delayed. Customers may be more likely to file a late delivery complaint if their order takes a long time to ship. Recommendations:

Retailers should use a shipping carrier that is reliable and has a good track record of on-time deliveries. Retailers should offer shipping insurance to customers who are concerned about late deliveries. Retailers should have a process in place for handling late delivery complaints quickly and efficiently.

Order item product price vs. sales per customer¶

Correlation coefficient: 0.781781 Strength: Strong Direction: Positive Interpretation: Customers who buy more expensive products tend to spend more money overall. Possible explanations:

Customers who are willing to spend more money on a product are also more likely to spend more money on other products and services. Customers who buy more expensive products may be more affluent and have higher disposable incomes. Retailers may bundle more expensive products together or offer discounts on multiple purchases, which encourages customers to spend more money. Recommendations:

Retailers should offer a variety of price points to appeal to customers with different budgets. Retailers should use cross-selling and upselling techniques to encourage customers to buy more expensive products. Retailers should offer loyalty programs and other rewards to customers who spend more money.

Order item discount vs. order item discount rate¶

Correlation coefficient: 0.659955 Strength: Strong Direction: Positive Interpretation: Orders with higher discounts tend to have higher discount rates. Possible explanations:

Retailers may offer higher discounts on items that are already on sale. Retailers may use tiered discounts, which give customers a higher discount the more they spend. Retailers may offer personalized discounts to customers who have a history of spending money with them. Recommendations:

Retailers should use a variety of discounting strategies to appeal to different customers. Retailers should track the effectiveness of their discounting strategies and make adjustments as needed. Retailers should be careful not to over-discount their products, as this can lead to lower profits.

Order item profit ratio vs. order item quantity¶

Correlation coefficient: -0.476232 Strength: Moderate Direction: Negative Interpretation: Orders with higher profit ratios tend to have lower quantities. Possible explanations:

Retailers may be more likely to sell items with higher profit ratios in smaller quantities, as this maximizes their profits. Customers may be less likely to buy items with higher profit ratios in large quantities, as they may be more expensive or unnecessary. Retailers may offer special discounts on items with higher profit ratios, which encourages customers to buy them in smaller quantities. Recommendations:

Retailers should track the profitability of their products and make adjustments to their pricing and inventory levels as needed. Retailers should use targeted marketing campaigns to promote items with higher profit ratios to customers who are most likely to buy them. Retailers should consider offering bundle discounts on items with lower profit ratios to encourage customers to buy them in larger quantities.

Key Observations¶

Days for shipping (real) has a moderate positive correlation with days for shipment (scheduled) (0.515880) and late_delivery_risk (0.401415). This means that orders that take longer to ship are more likely to be shipped late. Order item product price has a strong positive correlation with sales per customer (0.781781) and order item total (0.789948). This means that customers who buy more expensive products tend to spend more money overall. Order item discount has a strong positive correlation with order item discount rate (0.659955), which means that orders with higher discounts tend to have higher discount rates. Order item profit ratio has a strong negative correlation with order item quantity (-0.476232), which means that orders with higher profit ratios tend to have lower quantities.

Inferences¶

Based on the heatmap, we can infer the following:

Orders that take longer to ship are more likely to be shipped late. This is likely because orders that take longer to ship are more likely to encounter unforeseen delays. Customers who buy more expensive products tend to spend more money overall. This is likely because customers who are willing to spend more money on a product are also more likely to spend more money on other products and services. Orders with higher discounts tend to have higher discount rates. This is likely because retailers offer higher discounts on items that are already on sale. Orders with higher profit ratios tend to have lower quantities. This is likely because retailers are more likely to sell items with higher profit ratios in smaller quantities.

Suggestions¶

Based on the inferences above, we can make the following recommendations:

Retailers should strive to ship orders as quickly as possible to reduce the risk of late deliveries. Retailers should offer discounts on products that are less popular or that have been sitting in inventory for a long time. Retailers should focus on selling products with high profit ratios, even if it means selling them in smaller quantities.

Q1 = df['Sales per customer'].quantile(.25)

LL = Q3 - 1.5*(IQR)
print(UL)
print(LL)

32.86999899999998

The calculated Upper Limit (UL) is approximately 461.93, and the Lower Limit (LL) is approximately 32.87. Any data point in the 'Sales per customer' column that is higher than 461.93 or lower than 32.87 would be considered an outlier based on the 1.5 * IQR [Inter-Quartile Range] rule.

def classifiermodel(model_f,xf_train, xf_test,yf_train,yf_test):
    model_f=model_f.fit(xf_train,yf_train) # Fitting train data for fraud detection
    yf_pred=model_f.predict(xf_test)
    accuracy_f=accuracy_score(yf_pred, yf_test) #Accuracy for fraud detection
    recall_f=recall_score(yf_pred, yf_test) #Recall score for  fraud detection
    conf_f=confusion_matrix(yf_test, yf_pred)# fraud detection
    f1_f=f1_score(yf_test, yf_pred)#fraud detection
    print('Model paramters used are :',model_f)
    print('Accuracy of fraud status is        :', (accuracy_f)*100,'%')
    print('Recall score of fraud status is        :', (recall_f)*100,'%')
    print('Conf Matrix of fraud status is        :\n',  (conf_f))
    print('F1 score of fraud status is        :', (f1_f)*100,'%')

The F1 score is a harmonic mean of the precision and recall scores, and it takes into account both the model's ability to correctly predict fraudulent transactions and its ability to avoid predicting non-fraudulent transactions as fraudulent.

The K-Nearest Neighbors Classifier model with n_neighbors=1 has a high accuracy of 98.01%, meaning that it correctly predicts the fraud status of most transactions. However, the recall score of 60.09% is relatively low, meaning that the model misses a significant number of fraudulent transactions.

This is likely due to the fact that the model is using a very small neighborhood size. With a neighborhood size of 1, the model is only considering the most similar transaction to the current transaction when making a prediction. This can lead to the model missing fraudulent transactions that are slightly different from the transactions in the training data.

Additionally, the K-Nearest Neighbors Classifier model is susceptible to noise in the data. If the training data contains a lot of noisy data, the model may not be able to learn the true relationships between the features and the target variable. This can also lead to the model missing fraudulent transactions.

Despite these limitations, the K-Nearest Neighbors Classifier model with n_neighbors=1 is a relatively simple and efficient model to train and predict with. It is also a good model for fraud detection because it can be easily adapted to new data.

The F1 score of 72.11% indicates that the model has a good balance between precision and recall. This is important for fraud detection, as it is important to both correctly identify fraudulent transactions and avoid incorrectly identifying non-fraudulent transactions as fraudulent.
